00:40:51.390 --> 00:40:54.440
So that's the Alexandrov
implementation.

00:40:54.440 --> 00:40:57.410
This is by, I think, a student
of Bobenko and Izmestiev.

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:04.440
One quick question
about-- running out

00:41:04.440 --> 00:41:07.460
of time-- about
the nonconvex case.

00:41:07.460 --> 00:41:10.350
So we're doing all this work
about making convex surfaces.

00:41:10.350 --> 00:41:13.350
I said nonconvex
case is trivial.

00:41:13.350 --> 00:41:15.690
In a sense, the decision
problem is trivial.

00:41:15.690 --> 00:41:17.980
It's not an easy
theorem to prove.

00:41:17.980 --> 00:41:22.040
And aha, taped it up.

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:26.430
It follows from what's called
the Burago-Zalgaller theorem.

00:41:26.430 --> 00:41:30.320
And it says that if you tap
any polyhedral metric-- so that

00:41:30.320 --> 00:41:34.190
means you take a polygon,
you glue it however you want.

00:41:34.190 --> 00:41:35.409
You could even add boundary.

00:41:35.409 --> 00:41:37.950
Pick any polyhedron metrics, so
you take any polygon and glue

00:41:37.950 --> 00:41:39.280
it however you want.

00:41:39.280 --> 00:41:40.750
It could have handles.

00:41:40.750 --> 00:41:42.390
It could be a doughnut.

00:41:42.390 --> 00:41:43.820
It could be whatever.

00:41:43.820 --> 00:41:49.290
Then it has an isometric
polyhedral realization in 3D.

00:41:49.290 --> 00:41:51.614
So there is a way-- so
we're doing it abstractly.

00:41:51.614 --> 00:41:52.780
We're gluing stuff together.

00:41:52.780 --> 00:41:53.905
It's kind of topologically.

00:41:53.905 --> 00:41:55.290
We don't know what we're doing.

00:41:55.290 --> 00:41:57.190
But then there is a way
to actually embed it

00:41:57.190 --> 00:42:00.790
as a polyhedral surface
in 3D without stretching

00:42:00.790 --> 00:42:02.120
any of the lengths.

00:42:02.120 --> 00:42:05.120
So it's a folding of
the piece of paper.

00:42:05.120 --> 00:42:07.330
It could have creases in
it, will have actually

00:42:07.330 --> 00:42:09.310
tons of creases in it.

00:42:09.310 --> 00:42:12.622
And it has exactly the
right-- it connects

00:42:12.622 --> 00:42:14.580
all the things you want
it to connect together.

00:42:14.580 --> 00:42:17.640
It's kind of crazy.

00:42:17.640 --> 00:42:21.800
Furthermore, it could
be self-crossing.

00:42:21.800 --> 00:42:26.020
But if your surface
is either orientable--

00:42:26.020 --> 00:42:32.840
so it doesn't have any cross
caps or Mobius strips in it--

00:42:32.840 --> 00:42:36.070
or it has boundary,
then there's even

00:42:36.070 --> 00:42:38.250
a way to do without crossings.

00:42:38.250 --> 00:42:40.640
So that's basically all
the cases we care about.

00:42:40.640 --> 00:42:44.630
You could glue this together
into a sphere or into a disk

00:42:44.630 --> 00:42:48.789
or into a torus or
two-handled torus or whatever.

00:42:48.789 --> 00:42:50.330
No matter what you
do, there is a way

00:42:50.330 --> 00:42:53.930
to embed it in 3D as a
presumably nonconvex very

00:42:53.930 --> 00:42:56.440
creased surface.

00:42:56.440 --> 00:42:58.830
This is a hard to prove.

00:42:58.830 --> 00:43:00.570
If you're familiar
with Nash's embedding

00:43:00.570 --> 00:43:02.650
theorem about embedding
Riemannian surfaces,

00:43:02.650 --> 00:43:05.510
it uses a bunch of techniques
from there called spiraling

00:43:05.510 --> 00:43:07.250
perturbations,
which I don't know.

00:43:07.250 --> 00:43:10.620
And one description I read
calls the resulting surfaces

00:43:10.620 --> 00:43:14.730
"strongly corrugated," which
I think means tons of creases.

00:43:14.730 --> 00:43:16.280
It is finitely many creases.

00:43:16.280 --> 00:43:17.220
That's the theorem.

00:43:17.220 --> 00:43:18.262
There's no bound on them.

00:43:18.262 --> 00:43:19.845
As far as I know,
there's no algorithm

00:43:19.845 --> 00:43:20.860
to compute this thing.

00:43:20.860 --> 00:43:22.734
I've never seen a picture
of them, otherwise,

00:43:22.734 --> 00:43:23.750
I'd show it to you.

00:43:23.750 --> 00:43:27.270
So lots of open problems
in making this real.

00:43:27.270 --> 00:43:29.810
But at least the decision
problem is kind of boring.

00:43:29.810 --> 00:43:30.920
You do any gluing.

00:43:30.920 --> 00:43:33.044
It will make a nonconvex thing.

00:43:33.044 --> 00:43:34.960
To find that thing is
still pretty interesting

00:43:34.960 --> 00:43:36.430
question though.

